AB  - News waves attracting a lot of media attention may distract the mass media-and the public-from other, more important and pressing problems. This study assumes that killer issues and leader issues may distract or attract attention towards victim or follower issues, respectively. Furthermore, it is assumed that key events and corresponding news waves induce and drive issue relationship processes. To investigate the impact of news waves on the issue composition in print media, content analysis data about 101 news waves and 20 issue areas were utilized. Key findings are (a) some issues characteristically interact with each other (i.e., stable relationships were found); (b) issues differ in the dominant kind of role they play in issue relationships (e. g., "budget" is a follower issue, "EU affairs" a victim issue); (c) news waves within competing or related issues significantly influence the emphasis of issues over time.
